"description": "<p>Holiday Greetings Everybody, the eggnog is my only excuse for topic tardiness, but alas here it is.</p> <p><b>Substance</b></p> <p>It seems like we may have a smaller group, so I’d like to explore people’s perspectives on an often neglected topic; however, one that underpins all other assertions. This topic is substance. What do you think reality is made of? Is it animal, mineral or vegetable? Aristotle proposed his atomos, which underpins today’s natural philosophy of atomism. Wiki describes atomism as “the theory that all the objects in the universe are composed of very small, indestructible building blocks - atoms (Aristotle, Metaphysics, I, 4, 985 b, 10-15).” But what connects such irreducible items. Aristotle himself gets in a little trouble with his notion of potentiality whereby object A can only become object B if it was already B potentially. In some sense B-ness must be present already in A for it to transform into B; otherwise, catastrophic change would be the only means of change.(1) Dualism, on the other hand, posits that the connection between A and B is beyond the physical realm. For example, god could relate each little discrete node of space and time. This way they never have to overlap or intermingle. Each particle in physical substance is told what to do by some otherwise divine substance. We merely perceive a re-arrangement of these indivisible “atoms”. Spinoza, on the other hand, advocated for Monism; the idea that there is only one substance. Whether one perceives it as divine or material is a function of that person’s perspective. For Spinoza all modes of reality are attributes of just one substance. In this way object A is potentially any other object for it is formed out of the same continuous substance.</p> <p>This may seem an esoteric question to some, but all questions whether ontological, epistemological or even scientific would be served by begging this question before any warrants are granted that underpin some claim. Questions of subject/object, freewill and semiotics serve themselves by addressing any assumptions about substance before articulating a model of reality no matter how esoteric or practical. I claim this is so, because all relationships between entities living or not rely on the exchange of ordered patterns; whether atoms conversing via the 4 universal forces or two people conversing in a common language. For some, these ordered patterns are composed of discrete states, like those in a computer. What governs these states is some other meta-state; whether it be an algorithm or god. Others claim that ordered patterns are both the objects and their means of relating. To them A is already partly B and vise versa. In any case, presupposing the nature of the underlying substance bears significantly on how a proposed model can claim to represent reality.</p> <p>Questions of freewill and causality are especially dependant on this question. Throughout human history, we wonder whether we are the cause of our own discord or is it imposed upon us from without? Does my action change someone’s mind, does our collective behavior create the market or vise versa, can my action change the behavior of a terrorist? Is happiness a thing, is it contagious and can it be made? One way to see these questions in a new way is to wonder what they are made of and how these substances may relate and potentially form each other.</p> <p>I look forward to your thoughts on these questions. As usual, we will meet at 7pm, settle in, meet and greet, and kick off the topic at 7:30pm.</p> <p>Cheers,<br/>Josh</p> <p>(1) Sir David Ross, Aristotle, Routledge Press, 1995, p.182</p> ",
