"description": "<p>The general focus of our last meet (Hermeneutics) was the statement:</p> <p>To understand oneself is thus to understand the genealogy of one's own intellectual horizon.</p> <p>While our conversation went far on the notion of the genealogy of one's intellectual horizon, it did not go far on the notion of understanding oneself. For this meet, I propose that we focus on the notion of self understanding - in an open way that is not necessarily linked to hermeneutics or our discussion last time generally.</p> <p>Three questions we might consider regarding self understanding are:</p> <p>[1] What is self understanding?<br/>[2] Given that there is something that is self understanding, should it be valued?<br/>[3] If self understanding should be valued, why?</p> <p>Regarding the first question, we might ask what it is that a person with self understanding understands as such, or how a person with high self understanding differs from a person with low self understanding. An outcome in these considerations might be that while the expression 'self understanding' has a few coherent uses, there is no general inherent condition of a person that we should deem self understanding or the lack thereof.</p> <p>But given that the notion of self understanding is coherent, it might be asked how important it is as a value, if it is a value at all. To illustrate, while self understanding is something that a person might be concerned to develop, perhaps it represents merely a kind of self absorption that undermines such other potential values as being flexible, cooperative and outwardly focused. Generally, is self understanding something we should be concerned to cultivate, or merely something to consider when a problem arises, if even then?</p> <p>If it is sensed that self understanding is something to be valued and cultivated, it might be asked why this is, what specific values it realizes, for example.</p> <p>This is a topic that we can bring our everyday philosophizing to.</p> <p>As usual, we'll convene at 7pm, meet and greet, and start the topic when we're settled in. Btw, last time our venue was rather loud for the first hour or so due to a game on the television, but that isn't typical.</p> <p>Cheers,<br/>Paul M. Paolini</p> ",
