"description": "<p>For this meet, member David Shalen is our guest topic-framer and slated co-moderator. In his essay below, David raises questions concerning the nature of ethical and aesthetic values and how such values coexist. Additional reading on the topic is open and encouraged. As usual, we'll convene at 7pm and start the discussion when we're settled in. Cheers, Paul</p> <p>Does Aesthetics Come at the Expense of Ethics? by David Shalen</p> <p>The problem of the relationship between ethics and aesthetics has troubled philosophy since its inception and humanity longer. It has spawned almost as many questions as theories to address those questions, but the question raised here is a recurring one. Put more precisely, it is the question of whether following one's aesthetic bliss, whether through creation or appreciation of arts and aesthetic artifacts, hinder's one's tendency to follow one's own ethical concerns, whatever precise form those happen to take. The conflict is most clearly visible in the context that has likely generated most of the concern over human history, the context of weighing aesthetic and ethical considerations in making a decision. But it is not and cannot be limited to questions that arise in individual decisions.</p> <p>In considering the reasons for taking or not taking any course of actions, we often weigh the aesthetic and ethical effects of the actions. For example, in deciding whether to buy a beautiful rug made by poorly paid laborers, someone might compare their desire to have a well-appointed living room with their desire to help end an abusive institution. (It is assumed here that the subject's economic theory accomodates this framing of the decision.) But, supposing that the decision is made against buying the rug on ethical grounds, in what sense can it be said that the aesthetic pleasure of the individual has been diminished by the action? In all likelihood, the individual's aesthetics concerning his living room were themselves changed by the ethical dimension of his purchasing decision. As we all know from similar experiences, the apparent beauty of the rug in one's living room, the subjective sentiment at the heart of the aesthetics in the situation, can easily be altered by becoming conscious of some other consideration. It would be easy to conclude from the fact that we weigh the two dissimilar considerations against each other in making a decision that each comes at the expense of the other if they remained independent of each other throughout a decision-making process. This they clearly need not; if ethics can alter aesthetics as it comes up, it need not be said that aesthetics in general comes at the expense of ethics, but only that following a particular aesthetic unconditionally would indeed trump all other considerations, including ethical ones.</p> <p>Neither the idea of following an aesthetic unconditionally or contrastingly letting ethical considerations change it are particularly well-defined without a saying what an aesthetic is or describing its internal development in a theoretical environment free of other considerations, which space does not permit me to delve into here. We do however know that whatever the definitions or descriptions might be, the topic remains obtuse and theoretical, since, ordinarily, people do not follow aesthetic considerations in a vacuum. The aesthetic dimension of life loses all meaning if it is subject to a rule that no considerations that are not properly aesthetic can change them, simply because it would then become completely random with regard to life's other dimensions. This entails that any particular aesthetic judgement must be subject to being changed by life's other concerns to be a valid criterion of judgment at all. Likewise ethical judgments refer to other considerations almost by definition; people are to be protected by ethical behavior so that they may enjoy life's pleasures, including aesthetic pleasures which we must assume are at least somewhat akin to ours.</p> <p>While it might thus be argued that all dimensions of judgement by nature exist to promote each other, the fact remains that in making a specific decision, we often weigh one consideration against another. And both ethics and aesthetics, while we freely speak of them as stable general dimensions of judgment, seem to exist only within the context of actual decisions. Our discussion of some real or ideal person's ethics or aesthetics are almost epiphenomenal to what they discuss. To make statements about what is ethical behavior in general is to be insensitive to the particular facts about a situation, while to speak of making decisions promoting aesthetic excellence in general is to suppose that one's tastes are shared with all others and will never change. In other words, the two criteria seem to require a situation to be handed down to them to make sense at all, and that situation includes both the tastes of the people involved and the likely effect of their actions on others. The famous conflict between ethics and aesthetics seems insoluble in the context of a particular decision; given two people of like aesthetics at the outset of a potential rug purchase, it is highly likely that one will follow, and the other ignore, his conscience concerning the condition of the rug weavers. How can we avoid saying that one has let his aesthetics trump his ethics, while the other has not?</p> <p>Perhaps we cannot, but we can ask in return if the refrainer has not succeeded in making his overall aesthetic experience of life richer by being willing to change it in response to ethical circumstances, which will likely cause him to have a larger range of aesthetic experiences in his life. This very control of the range of aesthetic experience by factors which are not themselves aesthetic may in fact be what makes talk of a real or ideal individual's general aesthetic more than a set of epiphenomenal after-the-fact remarks. Thus, if by aesthetic bliss we are to mean something other than instant gratification, in defining it we might very well want to consider an individual's aesthetic through an extended period rather than statically. If the history of humanity provides any analogy to this life course, a visit to the Metropolitan Museum of Art (or a combination of San Francisco Museums) would convince us that ethics in general enlivens aesthetics; the great diversity of art in the museum is very heavily inspired by the evolving ethical concerns of the societies that produced it. Most of us grasp this concept so well that we are in fact prone to exaggerate this ethical history by ignoring the equally crucial technical developments that permitted the evolution witnessed in such a collection. Yet it is difficult for us to understand the interplay between aesthetics and ethics dynamically rather than statically outside the context of art history or some other narrow discipline. Again, if we cannot explain our aesthetic development without also explaining much about our ethical development, how and why should every episode of this development treat ethics and aesthetics as independent entities often in conflict with each other? A possible simple answer states that following one's aesthetic bliss is not the way to promote it, but this seems like a draconian maxim that would rob life of its' aesthetic character if t aken literally. More subtle answers must be possible, since we humans have almost always made more subtle decisions concerning the ethical and aesthetic dimensions of life. ***</p> ",
